  "response_text": "**Introduction to P, NP, and NP-complete problems**\n\nIn computer science, the complexity of a problem is a measure of the amount of time or resources required to solve it. The three main categories of problem complexity are P, NP, and NP-complete.\n\n### P (Polynomial Time)\n\nA problem is considered to be in P if it can be solved in a reasonable amount of time (polynomial time) by a computer. In other words, the time it takes to solve the problem grows polynomially with the size of the input. This means that if the input size doubles, the time it takes to solve the problem also doubles.\n\n**Example: Sorting a list of numbers**\n\nSorting a list of numbers is a P problem. The time it takes to sort a list of n numbers is proportional to n log n, which is a polynomial function.\n\n### NP (Nondeterministic Polynomial Time)\n\nA problem is considered to be in NP if it can be verified in a reasonable amount of",
